[The more we look for this disease, the more likely we are to find it. However, because intestines were used, as mentioned in the 1st article, it implies the calves are deceased. So does this virus have the potential to kill calves, or cause such massive diarrhea that the fluid loss and imbalances in young calves is more than they are capable of overcoming? Likely, we have a lot more to learn about this virus, and it is definitely something to keep on the diagnostic radar for ranchers and veterinarians. - Mod.TG

